    97	### D.3 Auth flow — HTTP Basic via per-experiment credential helper
    98	
    99	The reference Gitea is exposed on plain HTTP inside the compose
   100	network (no TLS). That matches the existing soft-isolation
   101	posture documented in §7 of
   102	[`spec/v0/reference-bindings/worker-host-subprocess.md`](../../spec/v0/reference-bindings/worker-host-subprocess.md):
   103	the reference deployment trades isolation for operational
   104	simplicity, and a hardened deployment substitutes a TLS-fronted
   105	Gitea behind the same `git://` URL. We document this caveat
   106	alongside the existing DooD soft boundary; the secret-handling
   107	boundary widens by exactly one channel (now the eden user's
   108	Gitea password is also visible to anyone with daemon access).
   109	
   110	setup-experiment.sh, after starting Gitea + waiting for healthy:
   111	
   112	1. Generate a per-experiment password `GITEA_REMOTE_PASSWORD`
   113	   (32 hex bytes; same shape as other reference secrets).
   114	2. Provision the eden user (idempotent — first checks via
   115	   `gitea admin user list`):
   116	
   117	   ```bash
   118	   docker compose exec -T gitea gitea admin user create \
   119	       --username eden \
   120	       --password "${GITEA_REMOTE_PASSWORD}" \
   121	       --email eden@invalid \
   122	       --admin
   123	   ```
   124	
   125	   Re-running with a different password updates the existing
   126	   user (`gitea admin user change-password`) so re-runs of
   127	   setup-experiment with new env files don't desync.
   128	3. Generate a per-experiment access token (used only by
   129	   setup-experiment for repo creation, NOT by workers; workers
   130	   use Basic auth):
   131	
   132	   ```bash
   133	   curl -fsS -u "eden:${GITEA_REMOTE_PASSWORD}" \
   134	       -X POST http://localhost:${GITEA_HOST_PORT}/api/v1/users/eden/tokens \
   135	       -d '{"name":"setup","scopes":["write:repository"]}'
   136	   ```
   137	
   138	4. Create the repo `eden/<EXPERIMENT_ID>.git` via
   139	   `POST /api/v1/user/repos` (idempotent — handle 409).
   140	5. Write the **credential-helper script** to a host-side path
   141	   `${COMPOSE_DIR}/.gitea-creds-${EXPERIMENT_ID}/credential-helper.sh`,
   142	   substituting the password into a template. The script:
   143	
   144	   ```sh
   145	   #!/bin/sh
   146	   case "$1" in
   147	     get)
   148	       cat <<EOF
   149	   username=eden
   150	   password=__GITEA_REMOTE_PASSWORD__
   151	   EOF
   152	       ;;
   153	   esac
   154	   ```
   155	
   156	   Mode 0755. Mounted read-only into every worker host container
   157	   at `/etc/eden/credential-helper.sh`.
   158	
   159	Workers configure git to use the helper via repo-local config
   160	written at clone time (NOT global config — keeps the secret out
   161	of the worker's home dir):
   162	
   163	```bash
   164	git -c credential.helper="/etc/eden/credential-helper.sh" \
   165	    -c http.extraHeader="" \
   166	    clone http://gitea:3000/eden/<EXPERIMENT_ID>.git \
   167	    /var/lib/eden/repo
   168	git -C /var/lib/eden/repo config credential.helper \
   169	    "/etc/eden/credential-helper.sh"
   170	```
   171	
   172	Subsequent `git fetch` / `git push` invocations from that repo
   173	pick up the helper automatically. The chunk-10d-followup-A
   174	soft-boundary caveat (§7) is extended to cover this: the eden
   175	user's Gitea password is on the host filesystem at
   176	`${COMPOSE_DIR}/.gitea-creds-<id>/credential-helper.sh` mode 0755,
   177	readable by anyone on the host and (under DooD) by any
   178	concurrent `*_command`.
