   180	### D.4 setup-experiment.sh sequencing — option (a) selected
   181	
   182	`setup-experiment.sh` already runs the bare-repo seed step
   183	synchronously via `compose run --rm --no-deps eden-repo-init`.
   184	This sub-chunk extends that pattern: setup-experiment now also
   185	**brings Gitea up** synchronously (before the rest of the stack)
   186	and provisions it before writing the operator's next-step
   187	instructions. No deferred work in the operator's own
   188	`compose up`.
   189	
   190	Concrete sequence (replaces the current "seed bare repo, write
   191	.env, exit" flow):
   192	
   193	1. Generate / preserve all secrets (existing flow), including
   194	   the new `GITEA_REMOTE_PASSWORD`.
   195	2. Write the partial `.env` (without `EDEN_BASE_COMMIT_SHA` —
   196	   filled in step 7).
   197	3. **Bring Gitea up:**
   198	   `docker compose --env-file "$ENV_FILE" up -d --wait gitea`
   199	   (uses Gitea's existing healthcheck).
   200	4. **Provision Gitea** per §D.3 (eden user, access token, repo).
   201	5. **Write the credential-helper script** under
   202	   `${COMPOSE_DIR}/.gitea-creds-${EXPERIMENT_ID}/`.
   203	6. **Seed + push** via `compose run --rm --no-deps eden-repo-init`,
   204	   which now takes a `--push-to <url>` flag and pushes the seed
   205	   commit to Gitea after creating the local bare repo.
   206	7. Capture the seed SHA, replace the `.env` placeholder
   207	   (existing pattern).
   208	8. Print operator next-steps (existing — `compose up -d --wait`).
   209	
   210	The shared `eden-bare-repo` volume is removed from `compose.yaml`
   211	in the cutover; `eden-repo-init` keeps writing to it locally only
   212	so the seed-and-push step is self-contained, then the volume is
   213	discarded by the existing `compose down -v` posture.
   214	
   215	**Idempotency:** all four provisioning operations (user create,
   216	token mint, repo create, ref push) are idempotent. Re-running
   217	setup-experiment with the same env file is a no-op for Gitea
   218	state. Re-running with a NEW env file (different
   219	`GITEA_REMOTE_PASSWORD`) updates the user's password via
   220	`gitea admin user change-password`.
   221	
   222	### D.5 Per-service compose changes
   223	
   224	Each worker host gains:
   225	
   226	- A *private* named volume for its clone:
   227	  `eden-implementer-repo`, `eden-evaluator-repo`,
   228	  `eden-orchestrator-repo` (no shared `eden-bare-repo` anymore).
   229	- The credential-helper script bind-mounted RO at
   230	  `/etc/eden/credential-helper.sh`.
   231	- A new `--gitea-url <http-url>` CLI flag on each host.
   232	
   233	Each worker host's startup logic:
   234	
   235	1. If `/var/lib/eden/repo` is not yet a git repo, `clone_from`
   236	   from Gitea via `clone --bare` (per §D.8a — all worker hosts
   237	   are bare clones).
   238	2. Otherwise, `git fetch --prune origin '+refs/heads/*:refs/heads/*'`
   239	   to refresh local heads and prune any local heads that no
   240	   longer exist on the remote (one-shot orphan cleanup as a
   241	   fetch side effect).
   242	3. **Integrator-only: reconcile orphan REMOTE refs.** The
   243	   orchestrator's startup additionally walks the remote
   244	   `trial/*` heads via `git ls-remote origin 'refs/heads/trial/*'`
   245	   and for each, calls `Store.read_trial(trial_id)`. If the
   246	   trial doesn't exist OR has no `trial_commit_sha` (i.e.,
   247	   `trial.integrated` was never committed), the integrator
   248	   issues `delete_remote_ref` against Gitea to clean up. This
   249	   is the recovery rule for the §D.6 step-4a failure mode:
   250	   "remote publish succeeded, store write failed, remote
   251	   compensating delete failed" — the next integrator startup
   252	   notices the remote ref has no matching `trial_commit_sha`
   253	   and removes it. The check is store-authoritative because
   254	   the spec's chapter 6 §3.4 makes the store the source of
   255	   truth for "is this trial integrated."
   256	4. Enter the normal poll loop.
   257	
   258	**Per-operation freshness for long-lived clones.** The orchestrator
   259	loop and the web-ui's admin/implementer modules are long-lived;
   260	remote refs change under their feet between the startup fetch and
   261	the next operation. Two policies:
   262	
   263	- **Read-before-write:** any service path that's about to write a
   264	  ref via `repo.create_ref` first runs `git fetch origin <ref>`
   265	  to refresh its local view. This keeps `--force-with-lease`'s
   266	  expected-old-sha aligned with the remote.
   267	- **Read-before-display:** the web-ui admin work-refs GC page
   268	  (chunk-9e) runs `git fetch origin '+refs/heads/work/*:refs/heads/work/*'`
   269	  on every GET so the operator's view matches the remote. The
   270	  per-op fetch budget here is one HTTP roundtrip + a small ref
   271	  list, well under 100ms in the reference deployment.
   272	
   273	Failure mode: if Gitea is unreachable at startup, the host exits
   274	non-zero and compose's `restart: on-failure` (existing posture)
   275	retries until healthy. Mid-operation Gitea unreachability raises
   276	`GitTransportError` from `eden_git`; service-level handlers catch
   277	it role-specifically per [chapter 3](../../spec/v0/03-roles.md):
   278	
   279	- **Implementer** (chapter 3 §3.3): infrastructure faults during
   280	  worker-side execution map to `ImplementSubmission(status="error",
   281	  trial_id=..., commit_sha=None)`. The trial composite-commits
   282	  to `error` atomically with the task transition. Same posture
   283	  as today's chunk-10d "subprocess timeout" path.
   284	- **Evaluator** (chapter 3 §4.4): infrastructure faults map to
   285	  `EvaluateSubmission(status="eval_error", trial_id=..., metrics=None)`.
   286	  The trial stays at its prior status (`success` from the
   287	  implementer) so the trial can be re-evaluated; this is the
   288	  spec-mandated distinction between `error` (worker-determined
   289	  bad outcome) and `eval_error` (infrastructure failure).
   290	- **Integrator** (chapter 6 §3.4): a transport failure during
   291	  `push_ref` is the same as a "rejected by remote" — local
   292	  rollback runs (step 4b only), no `trial.integrated`. A
   293	  transport failure during `delete_remote_ref` (step 4a) is
   294	  the §D.7c recovery case above.
   295	
   296	### D.6 Integrator (orchestrator) changes — explicit four-step flow
   297	
   298	The current integrator at
   299	[`reference/packages/eden-git/src/eden_git/integrator.py`](../../reference/packages/eden-git/src/eden_git/integrator.py)
   300	does (chapter 6 §3.2 / §3.4):
   301	
   302	```text
   303	1. local create_ref     # CAS-guarded
   304	2. store.integrate_trial
   305	3. on store failure: local delete_ref (compensating)
   306	```
   307	
   308	After this sub-chunk, the flow becomes a literal four-step
   309	publish-then-commit-then-rollback ladder:
   310	
   311	```text
   312	1. local create_ref           # CAS-guarded local
   313	2. remote push_ref            # publish to Gitea (force-with-lease)
   314	3. store.integrate_trial      # writes trial_commit_sha + trial.integrated
   315	4. on store failure:
   316	   4a. remote delete_ref      # compensating remote delete
   317	   4b. local delete_ref       # compensating local delete
   318	```
   319	
   320	The new step 4a — **remote compensating delete** — is load-bearing
   321	under chapter 6 §3.4: leaving `trial/*` on Gitea without the
   322	matching `trial.integrated` event in the store is a protocol
   323	violation, because the next replay of the event log would see a
   324	ref that no event explains. We MUST run step 4a before step 4b
   325	so a re-tried integration sees a clean Gitea slate.
   326	
   327	`GitRepo` therefore needs a fourth new method:
   328	
   329	- `delete_remote_ref(ref: str, expected_sha: str | None) -> None`
   330	  — `git push origin --delete <ref>` with a CAS guard via
   331	  `--force-with-lease=<ref>:<sha>`. If the remote ref has
   332	  diverged (someone else integrated a different commit on the
   333	  same trial id), raise `RefRefused` and let the caller decide.
   334	
   335	If step 2 fails (push rejected — concurrent integrator won
   336	the race), only step 1's local ref exists; we run step 4b
   337	(local delete) and skip 4a. If step 3 fails after step 2
   338	succeeded, we run BOTH 4a and 4b. If step 4a itself fails (Gitea
   339	unreachable), we log a critical-severity diagnostic and leave
   340	the local ref in place — the next integrator startup's

